19 WHEREAS, many of the communities, settlements, and named locations on the map reflect
20 a way of life that has since evolved due to industrialization, urbanization, and shifts in
21 economic and social structuresâ€”even the towns of Stay and Tworun, once known as fertile
22 regions, saw opportunities dry up and shift toward Dahlonega; and
23 WHEREAS, preserving and recognizing this historical cartographic record allows for a
24 deeper appreciation of the county's heritage and provides insight into how landscapes such
25 as Duke's Creek and its yellow metal in 1828 shaped the area and the state; and
26 WHEREAS, the study and commemoration of these lost landmarks contribute to the broader
27 understanding of Georgia's small-town history and the forces that shaped its development
28 throughout the 20th century.
29 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES that
30 the members of this body recognize the historical significance of the 1911 Rand McNally
31 map of Lumpkin County, Georgia, and encourage further efforts to document, study, and
32 educate the public about the county's evolving geography and cultural legacy.
33 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Clerk of the House of Representatives is authorized
34 and directed to make appropriate copies of this resolution available for distribution to the
35 public and the press.
